27:54.506 --> 27:56.074 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
affect elections.

27:56.108 --> 28:01.146 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That's at PBS.org/NewsHour.

28:01.179 --> 28:11.757 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Stay with us.

28:11.790 --> 28:16.662 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Coming up on the "NewsHour":
for-profit colleges
under fire from the federal
government; and

28:16.695 --> 28:20.866 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
the French composer who
transformed animals
into a musical masterpiece.

28:20.899 --> 28:26.972 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But first: The Greek government
has begun
a pilot program to educate
refugee children

28:27.005 --> 28:31.710 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
stranded in the country, because
nations along
the migrant trail to Northern
Europe have

28:31.743 --> 28:33.378 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
closed their borders.

28:33.412 --> 28:37.883 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It is estimated there are more
than 20,000
children in refugee camps in
Greece.

28:37.916 --> 28:42.621 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The plan is being resisted by
some Greeks,
who say they worry about
refugees carrying

28:42.654 --> 28:46.825 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
infections and also about the
cultural change
the plan might bring.

28:46.858 --> 28:50.028 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
There have been protests in a
number of towns.

28:50.062 --> 28:53.365 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Special correspondent Malcolm
Brabant has
been looking at the issue, and
starts his

28:53.398 --> 28:56.168 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
report from Filippiada in
Western Greece.

28:56.201 --> 28:57.369 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: What's your
name?

28:57.402 --> 28:58.870 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MOHAMMED ZAITOON, Refugee: My
name's Mohammed.

28:58.904 --> 29:00.339 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: Where are you
from?

29:00.372 --> 29:01.340 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MOHAMMED ZAITOON: I'm from
Syria.

29:01.373 --> 29:02.407 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MALCOLM BRABANT: Yes.

29:02.441 --> 29:03.475 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And whereabouts in Syria are you
from?

29:03.508 --> 29:05.210 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MOHAMMED ZAITOON: I'm from -- I
live in Damascus.

29:05.243 --> 29:07.045 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: What's your
name?

29:07.079 --> 29:09.648 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
SELMA ZAITOON, Refugee: My name
is Selma.

29:09.681 --> 29:16.154 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MOHAMMED ZAITOON: I'm sad
because I don't
have school now.

29:16.188 --> 29:17.689 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And I want to go to school,
actually.

29:17.723 --> 29:21.226 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
SELMA ZAITOON: I would like now
to go to school.

29:21.259 --> 29:22.661 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
But I can't.

29:22.694 --> 29:27.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Now, here, I don't have school,
but I want
to go to school.

29:27.899 --> 29:33.605 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: The children's
formal education
ended 15 months ago, when they
left Syria.

29:33.639 --> 29:34.906 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Their father is Ammar Zaitoon.

29:34.940 --> 29:36.808 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
AMMAR ZAITOON, Refugee: I have
three children.

29:36.842 --> 29:40.479 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Two of them were in school.

29:40.512 --> 29:43.048 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And they always get top marks.

29:43.081 --> 29:47.919 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: Like tens of
thousands of
other refugees, the Zaitoons
wanted to settle

29:47.953 --> 29:52.958 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
elsewhere, but are now stuck in
Greece, where
anti-migrant sentiment is
significant, especially

29:52.991 --> 29:54.660 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
over the issue of education.

29:54.693 --> 29:58.296 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
AMMAR ZAITOON: We were
disappointed for that.

29:58.330 --> 30:04.703 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We want to know, why do they
don't want our
children to go to school?

30:04.736 --> 30:13.278 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We'd like something like to
speak with them
just in order to knowing us more
and more,

30:13.311 --> 30:15.247 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
that we are simple people.

30:15.280 --> 30:18.417 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We have the right to teach our
children.

30:18.450 --> 30:19.418 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
We like life.

30:19.451 --> 30:20.952 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
We like education.

30:20.986 --> 30:23.655 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Syrian people are very good
workers.

30:23.689 --> 30:26.858 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And when they study, they will
be good in
school.

30:26.892 --> 30:31.129 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: The family
lives in Filippiada,
a small town in Western Greece.

30:31.163 --> 30:36.201 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The parent-teacher association
told the Education
Ministry that under no
circumstances would

30:36.234 --> 30:42.374 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
they accept children from a
nearby camp, citing
fears about cultural differences
and infectious

30:42.407 --> 30:43.909 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
diseases.

30:43.942 --> 30:46.945 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They claimed their presence
would alter the
Greek character of the schools.

30:46.978 --> 30:50.282 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Most parents we approached
refused to talk.

30:50.315 --> 30:52.284 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
But Christos Gartzis spoke up.

30:52.317 --> 30:57.255 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
CHRISTOS GARTZIS, Greece
(through translator):
The education issue is not a
problem for us,

30:57.289 --> 31:02.127 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
as all these children have the
right to education,
but, first of all, the
government have to

31:02.160 --> 31:03.962 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
solve their housing problems.

31:03.995 --> 31:07.399 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They must be relocated to more
modern facilities.

31:07.432 --> 31:12.104 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
These children are going to be
permanently
ill during the winter, with
colds and coughs,

31:12.137 --> 31:14.473 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
viruses and maybe even
pneumonia.

31:14.506 --> 31:17.809 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What kind of schooling will we
be able to
offer them then?

31:17.843 --> 31:22.380 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: Several hundred
refugees,
mainly from Syria and
Afghanistan, live in

31:22.414 --> 31:26.985 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
tents in a former army base on
the outskirts
of Filippiada.

31:27.018 --> 31:31.590 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There are about 150 children who
do have the
occasional lesson from
volunteers.

31:31.623 --> 31:36.361 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But, mostly, they while away the
hours playing.

31:36.394 --> 31:40.732 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Filippiada's rejection of
refugee children
has put it beneath an
unfavorable spotlight,

31:40.766 --> 31:45.470 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and the conservative mayor,
Nikolaos Kalantzis,
has been trying to limit the
damage to the

31:45.504 --> 31:47.372 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
town's reputation.

31:47.405 --> 31:52.677 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NIKOLAOS KALANTZIS, Mayor of
Filippiada, Greece
(through translator): This is a
rather unique

31:52.711 --> 31:55.814 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
issue, in that the people who
have come here
don't actually want to stay
here.

31:55.847 --> 31:58.483 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They want to move on and are
seeking ways
to do so.

31:58.517 --> 32:01.553 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This is a matter of trying to
manage an interim
period for these people.

32:01.586 --> 32:03.321 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
At least that's the way I see
it.

32:03.355 --> 32:07.058 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, of course, this is not just
a problem
for Filippiada, but also for
Greece itself

32:07.092 --> 32:11.730 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and, in general, Europe, too,
since extreme
racist and nationalist feelings
are on the

32:11.763 --> 32:13.231 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
rise.

32:13.265 --> 32:16.802 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But in no way whatsoever could
Filippiada
be considered as a racist town.

32:16.835 --> 32:22.307 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: Like every
aspect of life
in Greece, education has been
hit by the country's

32:22.340 --> 32:24.910 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
six-year-long financial crisis.

32:24.943 --> 32:28.680 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The government has been forced
to lay off
teachers, and schools like this
are being

32:28.713 --> 32:34.319 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
run on half the budget
previously available
before the country went
bankrupt.

32:34.352 --> 32:40.492 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But headmaster George Gioldasis
is a strong
believer in the universal right
of children

32:40.525 --> 32:42.527 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to an education.

32:42.561 --> 32:46.198 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GEORGE GIOLDASIS, Headmaster
(through translator):
Problems definitely exist, but
we, the teachers,

32:46.231 --> 32:50.802 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
together with the parents and
parent-teacher's
association, as well as the
citizens of this

32:50.836 --> 32:55.373 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
town, are trying to solve them
with the limited
resources we have from the
municipality for

32:55.407 --> 32:57.309 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
education.

32:57.342 --> 33:01.012 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We're trying to at least solve
the basic problems
at the moment, but, in my
opinion, much more

33:01.046 --> 33:05.550 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
funding is going to be required
in order to
be able to provide the
infrastructure and

33:05.584 --> 33:10.121 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
prerequisites necessary for the
integration
of refugee children into our
schools.

33:10.155 --> 33:15.560 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: Greece's
education minister
says that the country has an
obligation to

33:15.594 --> 33:18.230 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
provide schooling for refugee
children.

33:18.263 --> 33:22.267 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And he's announced a program
where six schools
will open up in Athens, and
there'll be three

33:22.300 --> 33:24.402 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
others in towns around the
country.

33:24.436 --> 33:29.741 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, the minister says that this
initiative
will spread throughout Greece
through October.

33:29.774 --> 33:35.714 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The money to pay for it is
supposed to be
coming from a $1 billion fund
provided to

33:35.747 --> 33:40.819 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Greece by the European Union,
which is supposed
to help during the refugee
crisis.

33:40.852 --> 33:46.758 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
But there's been strong
resistance from nationalists
in the northern town of
Oraiokastro.

33:46.791 --> 33:50.128 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The rally organizers insisted
they were just
concerned citizens.

33:50.161 --> 33:55.467 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But some rhetoric sounded
similar to that
of the ultra-right Golden Dawn
Party.

33:55.500 --> 34:02.073 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
A riot police cordon prevented
clashes with
about 200 left-wing protesters.

34:02.107 --> 34:07.679 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The demonstrators emphasized
their orthodox
Christian heritage and
abhorrence of Islam.

34:07.712 --> 34:14.386 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Organizer Spiros Haravopoulos
says his ancestors
were victims of a Turkish
genocide on the

34:14.419 --> 34:18.490 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Black Sea nearly a century ago.

34:18.523 --> 34:20.525 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
"We are the Greeks.

34:20.558 --> 34:22.627 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That's who we are," he shouts.

34:22.661 --> 34:28.833 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This is a place where history is
never forgotten,
especially Greece's 400 years
under the Islamic

34:28.867 --> 34:30.869 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Ottoman Empire.

34:30.902 --> 34:33.939 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SPIROS HARAVOPOULOS, Protester
Organizer (through
translator): Of course we care
about the refugees,

34:33.972 --> 34:37.509 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
but let them go to other
countries, where
their own religion is widely
practiced, such

34:37.542 --> 34:40.312 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
as Saudi Arabia, Qatar, the
United Arab Emirates.

34:40.345 --> 34:43.648 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We have nothing against the
refugees, but
they have been brought here
without anyone

34:43.682 --> 34:46.151 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
having asked us if we want them
here.

34:46.184 --> 34:50.722 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Other people can't be allowed to
decide what
we want without us being asked
first, and

34:50.755 --> 34:52.691 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that's why we're protesting here
tonight.

34:52.724 --> 34:56.494 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Apart from the fact that they
have been terrifying
the people here, members of the
same government

34:56.528 --> 35:01.399 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that was voted into power by
citizens of this
place are calling us Nazis.

35:01.433 --> 35:09.507 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: Greece belongs
to the Greeks,
bellowed lawyer Dimitris
Mihakis, as he whipped

35:09.541 --> 35:11.409 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
up the crowd.

35:11.443 --> 35:12.577 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DIMITRIS MIHAKIS, Attorney
(through translator):
Are we supposed to allow this
and make our

35:12.610 --> 35:14.045 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
schools just for the minority?

35:14.079 --> 35:16.114 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Do they want a Greek minority
here in Greece?

35:16.147 --> 35:19.451 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We will not permit Greek schools
to be turned
into minority schools.

35:19.484 --> 35:23.321 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The plan is obviously to cause
problems and
unrest in this country in order
to satisfy

35:23.355 --> 35:27.092 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
some other fanciful geostrategic
plans which
they have in mind for us.

35:27.125 --> 35:32.330 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: Despite being
the object
of fear, suspicion and hate,
Ammar Zaitoon

35:32.364 --> 35:35.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
is remaining calm.

35:35.033 --> 35:43.975 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
AMMAR ZAITOON: We know that the
Greek people
were living the same situation
in the past.

35:44.009 --> 35:48.113 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And, actually, they are good
people.

35:48.146 --> 35:54.319 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I know, sometimes, sometimes,
you don't want
to see other people in your
country.

35:54.352 --> 35:58.790 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Sometimes, you don't want to see
another -- refugees
in your country.

35:58.823 --> 36:00.692 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
We respect that.

36:00.725 --> 36:03.495 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But, even so, they are very good
with us.

36:03.528 --> 36:10.301 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They receive us, and they are
trying to help
us as best as they can.

36:10.335 --> 36:16.274 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: As the rally
organizers danced
in the rain, they were condemned
as fascists

36:16.307 --> 36:21.046 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
by the left-wing protesters, who
chanted slogans
in support of the refugees.

36:21.079 --> 36:24.382 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
"Fatherland, faith, and family.

36:24.416 --> 36:28.553 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Long live Greece," he cried.

36:28.586 --> 36:36.461 align:left position:37.5%,start line:80% size:62.5%
The
government's determination to
provide classes

36:36.494 --> 36:39.030 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
nationwide will be severely
tested.

36:39.064 --> 36:42.100 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
A new battleground awaits the
war children.

36:42.133 --> 36:54.779 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour," I'm
Malcolm Brabant
in Northern Greece.

36:54.813 --> 37:01.386 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: This has been
a tough fall
in the world of for-profit
colleges, and for

37:01.419 --> 37:03.221 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
some of the students who attend
them.

37:03.254 --> 37:08.560 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The latest case, the bankruptcy
and abrupt
shutdown of ITT, one of the
largest for-profit

37:08.593 --> 37:10.261 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
technical schools.

37:10.295 --> 37:15.133 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Its 130 campuses were closed
last month after
the Department of Education said
it could

37:15.166 --> 37:20.672 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
no longer enroll new students
who relied on
federal loans and grants to
attend.

37:20.705 --> 37:24.609 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The Obama administration cited
problems with
its accreditation and concerns
that it was

37:24.642 --> 37:26.511 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
misleading students.

37:26.544 --> 37:31.483 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That has left about 35,000
students up in
the air over their future.

37:31.516 --> 37:35.587 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And it is the subject of our
weekly segment
on education, Making the Grade.

37:35.620 --> 37:38.356 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Paul Fain of the news site
Inside Higher Ed
joins me now.

37:38.389 --> 37:43.261 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, tell us, first of all, why
is ITT shutting
down?

37:43.294 --> 37:46.431 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
How important are they in the
pantheon of
the for-profit school system?

37:46.464 --> 37:49.901 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL FAIN, Inside Higher Ed:
They're one of
the biggest, one of the oldest,
most-established

37:49.934 --> 37:53.805 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
for-profit companies, with
campuses in 38
states.

37:53.838 --> 37:59.444 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They used to have campuses in 38
states, so
definitely one of the most
important players.

37:59.477 --> 38:04.983 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Year -- several tough years,
hemorrhaging
students and revenue.

38:05.016 --> 38:11.222 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And then they got hit with
several investigations
and lawsuits, federal and state,
some serious

38:11.256 --> 38:18.129 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
charges, the Consumer Financial
Protection
Bureau, the SEC both pursuing
them legally.

38:18.163 --> 38:23.668 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And then you had an accreditor
raising questions
about their record-keeping, and
the Fed finally

38:23.701 --> 38:26.171 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
said, too much risk for those
students and
taxpayers.

38:26.204 --> 38:30.542 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And there were just several
sanctions that
were really the end for the
company.

38:30.575 --> 38:31.876 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: But what about
those 35,000
students?

38:31.910 --> 38:32.944 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
What do they do?

38:32.977 --> 38:35.246 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PAUL FAIN: They are in a real
tough bind.

38:35.280 --> 38:37.348 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
They have two major choices.

38:37.382 --> 38:41.753 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
First, they can elect to have
their debt forgiven.

38:41.786 --> 38:47.859 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They can -- all the aid that
they had received,
the loans, they can have
forgiven by the federal

38:47.892 --> 38:49.060 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
government.

38:49.093 --> 38:50.995 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But, if they do that, their
credits don't
transfer.

38:51.029 --> 38:55.033 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If they seek to continue their
program somewhere
else, which might be tough as
is, they might

38:55.066 --> 39:00.572 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
not be able to find an option or
a similar
program nearby, those credits
won't count,

39:00.605 --> 39:02.073 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
if they take the payoff.

39:02.106 --> 39:05.076 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: And who is the
demographic
that goes to these schools?

39:05.109 --> 39:09.180 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL FAIN: Well, you're looking
at working
adults, basically, often the
first in their

39:09.214 --> 39:14.586 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
family to go to college, many
veterans at
ITT and some other for-profits,
and really

39:14.619 --> 39:20.024 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
just working adults looking to
advance themselves,
maybe to break into a career,
maybe to get

39:20.058 --> 39:25.597 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a credential, so they can get
out of a low-pay
job, folks who are working at
night, weekends

39:25.630 --> 39:27.098 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
to try to really advance
themselves.

39:27.131 --> 39:29.601 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: So, it wasn't
easy for them
to try to get this route.

39:29.634 --> 39:31.135 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And now they have put in all
this time.

39:31.169 --> 39:34.239 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
And if the credits don't
transfer, they might
be back at square one.

39:34.272 --> 39:35.974 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
PAUL FAIN: Absolutely.

39:36.007 --> 39:39.310 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
No matter what you think of ITT,
you have
to feel sorry or really
concerned about these

39:39.344 --> 39:43.214 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
students, because a lot of them
are really
just trying to get ahead to
really advance

39:43.248 --> 39:44.215 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
themselves.

39:44.249 --> 39:45.216 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
HARI SREENIVASAN: OK.

39:45.250 --> 39:46.217 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And put this in context.

39:46.251 --> 39:47.785 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
This isn't the first school.

39:47.819 --> 39:49.854 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This is just the latest school
in the for-profit
world that's had problems.

39:49.887 --> 39:52.290 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We heard about Corinthian a
while back.

39:52.323 --> 39:53.458 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And there's been other schools
as well.

39:53.491 --> 39:54.459 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
PAUL FAIN: Correct.

39:54.492 --> 39:57.295 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Corinthian was even larger,
72,000 students.

39:57.328 --> 39:59.063 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
A couple years ago, it shut
down.

39:59.097 --> 40:04.469 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now what remains of it in a
different owner's
hands is only about 10,000
students.

40:04.502 --> 40:10.842 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
A few years ago, about one in 10
students
in America were at for-profit
institutions.

40:10.875 --> 40:16.247 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That's declined to about 6
percent of the
total, so really an existential
crisis for

40:16.281 --> 40:17.248 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
these companies.

40:17.282 --> 40:19.017 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And there's a lot of reasons for
that.

40:19.050 --> 40:22.287 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But it's not clear what the
future is for
for-profit higher education.

40:22.320 --> 40:23.655 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Is it the
business model?

40:23.688 --> 40:24.956 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Is that working anymore?

40:24.989 --> 40:28.359 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You see -- you used to see ads
nonstop on
TV at late night.

40:28.393 --> 40:29.694 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And it was competitive.

40:29.727 --> 40:31.663 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It was DeVry and ITT and Phoenix
Online.

40:31.696 --> 40:33.031 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
PAUL FAIN: Right.

40:33.064 --> 40:34.699 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: And there were
so many different
opportunities.

40:34.732 --> 40:36.634 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
PAUL FAIN: And they were
booming.

40:36.668 --> 40:42.607 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You had massive growth coming
right after
the recession, as folks dropped
out of the

40:42.640 --> 40:48.046 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
economy and were really trying
to retool themselves,
and these schools reached out to
them.

40:48.079 --> 40:51.616 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They tended to be better than
their competitors
when it comes to advertising,
because they

40:51.649 --> 40:53.518 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
had the money to do that.

40:53.551 --> 40:55.320 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But several factors have hit
them.

40:55.353 --> 40:57.955 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I mean, first of all, the
recovery has recovered
a little bit.

40:57.989 --> 41:02.794 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, you have fewer folks looking
to go back
to school to try to find a job.

41:02.827 --> 41:11.903 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You have just waves of bad
publicity, investigations,
criticism by the media, by
lawmakers, primarily

41:11.936 --> 41:13.705 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Democrats, which I think has
taken a toll.

41:13.738 --> 41:16.507 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think the word for-profit has
a bit of a
stigma.

41:16.541 --> 41:19.243 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
And that's the companies
themselves who will
say that.

41:19.277 --> 41:22.880 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And I just think it's a harder
sell.

41:22.914 --> 41:26.184 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
A lot of them are a little bit
more expensive
than community colleges.

41:26.217 --> 41:30.888 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
They say they offer more
services to help
students, but it's a little
harder to get

41:30.922 --> 41:34.058 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
someone to pay $15,000 or more
to go to one
of these programs.

41:34.092 --> 41:37.762 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: But what do
the executives
at these companies say about
their plight

41:37.795 --> 41:39.731 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and how the environment has
changed?

41:39.764 --> 41:43.701 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL FAIN: Well, first of all,
they say they
have been treated unfairly, that
this administration

41:43.735 --> 41:48.940 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and Senate Democrats have
cracked down on
them more than the rest of
higher education.

41:48.973 --> 41:54.145 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There are questions about all of
higher education's
return on investment, the value
of a degree.

41:54.178 --> 41:58.916 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think it's quite clear that
the best way
to get a job is to get a degree.

41:58.950 --> 42:02.286 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But people are concerned about
student debt
on the whole.

42:02.320 --> 42:08.393 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But for-profit higher education
has really
received, I think, the first
wave of aggressive

42:08.426 --> 42:12.897 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
federal policy to try to make
sure students
are getting what they pay for.

42:12.930 --> 42:15.933 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Paul Fain of
the news site
Inside Higher Ed, thanks for
joining us.

42:15.967 --> 42:17.668 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
PAUL FAIN: Thanks for having me.

42:17.702 --> 42:20.738 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: And speaking
of student
debt, college affordability has
become an

42:20.772 --> 42:22.573 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
issue in the election.

42:22.607 --> 42:27.011 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We have been taking a look at
what's behind
the growth of that debt and just
how big a

42:27.044 --> 42:28.780 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
problem it is.

42:28.813 --> 42:33.284 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's part of our year-long
series How the
Deck Is Stacked, funded by the
Corporation

42:33.317 --> 42:35.086 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
for Public Broadcasting.

42:35.119 --> 42:38.623 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Our partners at "Frontline" and
Marketplace
put together a video explainer
that's been

42:38.656 --> 42:43.294 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
drawing some attention for
laying out the
landscape of student debt.

42:43.327 --> 42:45.396 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Marketplace host Kai Ryssdal is
our guide.

42:45.430 --> 42:51.169 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KAI RYSSDAL, Marketplace: Today,
student debt
is a staggering $1.3 trillion.

42:51.202 --> 42:56.240 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But how bad is that for the
economy and for
the people holding all that
debt?

42:56.274 --> 43:00.211 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There's a debate going on right
now, and some
experts argue, maybe it's not as
bad as we

43:00.244 --> 43:01.412 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
think.

43:01.446 --> 43:09.353 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I'm Kai Ryssdal, and this is How
the Deck
Is Stacked.

43:09.387 --> 43:11.189 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
One-point-three trillion
dollars.

43:11.222 --> 43:13.157 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
So, how did we get here?

43:13.191 --> 43:16.894 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One reason for the growth is
simply because
many more people have been going
to college.

43:16.928 --> 43:20.898 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
During the great recession, when
the economy
tanked, a lot of people couldn't
get a job,

43:20.932 --> 43:25.069 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
so they decided to go back to
school, and
most people can't pay for school
without taking

43:25.102 --> 43:26.370 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
out some student loans.

43:26.404 --> 43:30.408 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In 2008, about 29 million people
held student
debt.

43:30.441 --> 43:33.978 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
By 2015, that was up to 40
million people.

43:34.011 --> 43:36.013 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
More people in school equals
more overall
debt.

43:36.047 --> 43:42.019 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
At the same time, the cost of
college also
went up, while state funding for
higher education

43:42.053 --> 43:43.855 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
went down.

43:43.888 --> 43:49.427 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, despite the rise in debt,
some experts
say that this idea of a crisis
is overblown.

43:49.460 --> 43:53.231 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Student debt is much smaller
than mortgage
debt, and so they say that
shouldn't tank

43:53.264 --> 43:55.066 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the economy.

43:55.099 --> 43:58.870 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They also argue that, for most
of those 40
million people, taking on the
debt is going

43:58.903 --> 44:00.304 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to be OK.

44:00.338 --> 44:04.675 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The reality is, only 8 percent
of debt holders
owe more than $75,000.

44:04.709 --> 44:08.613 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And many of those people went to
graduate
school, which should increase
their earning

44:08.646 --> 44:10.414 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
potential.

44:10.448 --> 44:14.519 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Then there are the majority of
borrowers,
almost 70 percent, who owe less
than $25,000.

44:14.552 --> 44:18.289 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Now, that still is a whole lot
of money for
most of us.

44:18.322 --> 44:23.194 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, on average, people with a
bachelor's
degree make around $20,000 more
a year than

44:23.227 --> 44:24.996 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
those with only a high school
diploma.

44:25.029 --> 44:29.467 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, while it may be a struggle
in the short
term, chances are, most will be
able to pay

44:29.500 --> 44:31.502 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
it off.

44:31.536 --> 44:35.139 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But then there are the people
who are really
hurting, people who took out
loans, but didn't

44:35.172 --> 44:36.874 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
finish school.

44:36.908 --> 44:40.778 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Most of them owe less than
$10,000, which
might seem small, but they won't
be getting

44:40.811 --> 44:44.482 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the pay boost from a degree, and
yet still
have to pay back that debt.

44:44.515 --> 44:50.588 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And with bills to pay, interest
accruing,
and fees, they can get behind
pretty quickly.

44:50.621 --> 44:54.525 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For this group, the risk of
taking on the
debt might not have been worth
it.

44:54.559 --> 44:58.329 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But, for the majority of us, the
investment
might be.

44:58.362 --> 45:00.631 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Yet many of us don't feel that
way.

45:00.665 --> 45:04.201 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We know that because you told
us.

45:04.235 --> 45:08.072 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In our Marketplace/Edison
Research Poll, nearly
40 percent of you said the
education wasn't

45:08.105 --> 45:10.608 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
worth the debt.

45:10.641 --> 45:11.842 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Why is this?

45:11.876 --> 45:14.345 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Well, we're not anxious about
college debt
in a vacuum.

45:14.378 --> 45:15.580 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Right?

45:15.613 --> 45:17.548 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We have got a lot of other
economic worries
on our minds.

45:17.582 --> 45:21.719 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: That video
actually was
produced for the Web in 360
degrees, where

45:21.752 --> 45:25.022 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
you can point your phone in any
direction
to look around the story.

45:25.056 --> 45:35.099 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You can see the full story by
going to "Frontline"'s
Facebook page.

45:35.099 --> 45:40.338 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You can see the full story by
going to "Frontline"'s
Facebook page.

45:40.371 --> 45:45.810 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now "The Carnival of Animals"
and a famous
composer who felt he was
celebrated for the

45:45.843 --> 45:47.445 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
wrong thing.

45:47.478 --> 45:52.817 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Camille Saint Saens would have
celebrated
his 181st birthday this past
weekend.

45:52.850 --> 45:57.288 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Once again, pianist Rob Kapilow
joins Jeffrey
Brown to explore what makes
great music.

45:57.321 --> 45:59.056 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Rob Kapilow,
welcome.

45:59.090 --> 46:00.591 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ROB KAPILOW, Composer: Thanks
for having me.

46:00.625 --> 46:03.928 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: So, today, we're
marking the
birthday of Camille Saint Saens.

46:03.961 --> 46:08.132 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This is a story of a great
composer who didn't
quite get the legacy that he
wanted.

46:08.165 --> 46:11.502 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
ROB KAPILOW: During his
lifetime, I mean,
he was a famous composer, one of
the most

46:11.535 --> 46:14.972 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
famous composers in the world,
writing serious
operas, serious symphonies.

46:15.006 --> 46:17.074 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Tell us a little
bit about
him, for those who don't know.

46:17.108 --> 46:19.543 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROB KAPILOW: Well, you know, he
was also one
of the world's greatest musical
prodigies.

46:19.577 --> 46:23.514 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In fact, many people think he
was even more
of a prodigy than Mozart or
Mendelssohn.

46:23.547 --> 46:25.616 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
He started piano at
two-and-a-half.

46:25.650 --> 46:30.588 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He wrote his first piece at
four-and-a-half,
made a public debut at 10, in
which not only

46:30.621 --> 46:34.458 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
did he play two concertos and
write his own
cadenza, but, for an encore, he
offered to

46:34.492 --> 46:38.329 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
play any Beethoven sonata from
memory that
the audience wanted.

46:38.362 --> 46:44.101 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That's 32 sonatas at the age of
10, one of
the great musical proteges,
utterly famous,

46:44.135 --> 46:48.239 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
yet then, for a joke, he writes
this piece
that literally became his
legacy.

46:48.272 --> 46:51.842 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: So, "Carnival of
the Animals,"
written for a friend, becomes
this famous

46:51.876 --> 46:52.843 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
piece.

46:52.877 --> 46:54.745 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Tell us about it.

46:54.779 --> 46:57.148 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROB KAPILOW: Yes, it was a
little party piece,
and, in it, he took 14 animals
in this grand

46:57.181 --> 47:04.055 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
zoological fantasy, is what he
called it.

47:04.088 --> 47:08.959 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And each movement turns an
animal somehow
into music.

47:08.993 --> 47:13.364 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the simplest way is to take
the sound
of the actual animal, and, in
the first movement,

47:13.397 --> 47:14.365 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
that's what happens.

47:14.398 --> 47:20.438 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
A lion's roar is turned into
music.

47:20.471 --> 47:34.018 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, sometimes, for example, in
"Hemiones,"
which is a wild Tibetan donkey
famous for

47:34.051 --> 47:39.023 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
running at blinding speed up and
down rough
mountains, he turns the idea of
the animal

47:39.056 --> 47:44.328 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
into music, and turns that into
two pianists
running up and down the keyboard
at blinding

47:44.361 --> 47:47.765 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
speed in unison.

47:47.798 --> 47:56.040 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: He also has this
movement called
"The Pianists."

47:56.073 --> 47:57.341 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ROB KAPILOW: Yes.

47:57.374 --> 47:58.709 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: It's sort of a
joke, pianist
as an animal.

47:58.743 --> 47:59.710 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ROB KAPILOW: Yes.

47:59.744 --> 48:00.711 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It's just a joke.

48:00.745 --> 48:01.946 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I mean, it's like based on the
scale.

48:01.979 --> 48:05.149 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's based on these ridiculous
scales that
pianists do.

48:05.182 --> 48:10.354 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Maybe that's the animal that
annoys the neighbors
when the pianists are actually
playing.

48:10.387 --> 48:15.259 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Pianists as
animals in a sense.

48:15.292 --> 48:16.494 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
ROB KAPILOW: Pianists as
animals.

48:16.527 --> 48:17.495 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Anybody can be a joke.

48:17.528 --> 48:19.463 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Right.

48:19.497 --> 48:23.367 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: One movement,
"The Swan," next-to-last
movement, did become hugely --
maybe the most

48:23.400 --> 48:24.635 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
famous part.

48:24.668 --> 48:26.003 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ROB KAPILOW: It became the most
famous piece
he ever wrote.

48:26.036 --> 48:27.738 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And it's interesting.

48:27.772 --> 48:30.608 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's the only movement that he
actually allowed
to be published during his
lifetime.

48:30.641 --> 48:35.079 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: I visited with
Yo-Yo Ma last
year for a piece for the
"NewsHour," and he

48:35.112 --> 48:46.991 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
played "The Swan" for us.

48:47.024 --> 49:00.371 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, what makes "The Swan" work
so well?

49:00.404 --> 49:03.908 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROB KAPILOW: Well, I think
writing the piece
so quickly gave him access to
one of the most

49:03.941 --> 49:05.676 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
beautiful, simple melodies he
ever wrote.

49:05.709 --> 49:11.582 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I mean, it starts off with
nothing but the
two pianos being the rippling
waters, and

49:11.615 --> 49:14.518 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
a little crest of a wave.

49:14.552 --> 49:15.986 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Then everything focuses on the
cello.

49:16.020 --> 49:17.454 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
There were only three ideas.

49:17.488 --> 49:23.527 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
A swan's neck dips, the same
idea lower.

49:23.561 --> 49:30.301 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Then the swan's neck rises
gracefully on a
long note, and then a simple
scale.

49:30.334 --> 49:33.370 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
But one note makes it great.

49:33.404 --> 49:38.175 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
We stretch it out.

49:38.209 --> 49:47.384 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Instead of this, we get this
beautiful high
note on the cello.

49:47.418 --> 49:56.393 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We go on a journey with this, we
come back,
we repeat the whole thing a
second time, and

49:56.427 --> 49:59.997 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
there's a beautiful epilogue at
the end telling
us the message.

50:00.030 --> 50:05.603 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Then, for the first time, all of
a sudden,
the rippling waters stop.

50:05.636 --> 50:08.706 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We know something important is
being shared
with us now.

50:08.739 --> 50:14.345 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We journey with the piece's
three ideas, and
we finish with a simple scale
stretched out

50:14.378 --> 50:23.187 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
